 This problem is about combinations, not permutations, because the order of the two types of cheese does not matter. We can use the combination formula: 
\[
^nC_r = \frac{n!}{r!(n-r)!}
\]
where we have n options for the first cheese and (n-1) options for the second, and we divide by 2! to account for the fact that the order does not matter. Here, n = 9 (the number of cheeses). 
The total number of ways Alex can choose the cheese is:
\begin{align*}
\frac{9 \times 8}{2!} &= \frac{9 \times 8}{2 \times 1}\\
&= \fbox{36}
\end{align*}
Now, for each way of choosing the cheese, Alex has 10 ways of choosing a meat. Therefore, the total number of possible sandwiches Alex can make is:
10 \times 36 = \fbox{360}
